<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<p class="p">The LOD and LOQ were calculated from the calibration curve according to
 <disp-formula id="EEq1" class="disp-formula">
  <label class="label">(1)</label>
  <math id="M1" class="math">
   <mtable class="mtable">
    <mtr class="mtr">
     <mtd class="mtd">
      <mtext class="mtext">LOD</mtext>
      <mo class="mo">=</mo>
      <mfrac class="mfrac">
       <mrow class="mrow">
        <mn class="mn">3.3</mn>
        <mi class="mi">σ</mi>
       </mrow>
       <mi class="mi">s</mi>
      </mfrac>
      <mo class="mo">,</mo>
     </mtd>
    </mtr>
   </mtable>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>
 <disp-formula id="EEq2" class="disp-formula">
  <label class="label">(2)</label>
  <math id="EEq2EAAAHDCCCA" class="math">
   <mtable class="mtable">
    <mtr class="mtr">
     <mtd class="mtd">
      <mtext class="mtext">LOQ</mtext>
      <mo class="mo">=</mo>
      <mfrac class="mfrac">
       <mrow class="mrow">
        <mn class="mn">10</mn>
        <mi class="mi">σ</mi>
       </mrow>
       <mi class="mi">s</mi>
      </mfrac>
      <mo class="mo">,</mo>
     </mtd>
    </mtr>
   </mtable>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>where 
 <italic class="italic">σ</italic> is the standard deviation of the response and 
 <italic class="italic">s</italic> is the slope of the calibration curve. The residual standard deviation of the line regression or the standard deviation of 
 <italic class="italic">y</italic>-intercepts of the line regression may be used as the standard deviation.
</p>
